Edges:
 A -> B = 1  
 A -> C = 4  
 C -> B = -6  



## 3. What Dijkstra Does

Start at A:

 Distance to B = 1  
 Distance to C = 4  

Since 1 is smaller the algorithm chooses B first.

It assumes the shortest path to B is 1.



## 4. The Problem

There is another path:

A -> C -> B  
= 4 + (-6)  
= -2  

The value -2 is smaller than 1.

So the real shortest path is -2 not 1.



## 5. Why It Fails

The algorithm makes a mistake because:

 It chooses the smallest value first
It does not go back and change it
 A negative weight can create a smaller value later



## 6. Conclusion

Dijkstra’s algorithm does not work with negative weights.

It only works when all edge weights are positive.
